      "article": "India’s Parliament has passed a landmark Digital Rights Bill aimed at strengthening online privacy, cybersecurity, and data protection regulations in the country. The legislation introduces stricter rules regarding collection, storage, and use of personal digital data by companies and online platforms. Government officials described the bill as an important step toward protecting citizens’ digital rights in an increasingly technology-driven society. The law also includes provisions related to user consent, data transparency, and penalties for unauthorized misuse of information. Opposition leaders and civil society organizations welcomed certain aspects of the legislation but demanded stronger safeguards against mass surveillance and misuse of state power. Technology companies are expected to update their digital practices to comply with the new regulations. Legal experts believe the bill could significantly influence India’s future digital governance framework while shaping public debate around privacy, freedom, and online security in the coming years."
